Title = {{Achieving water security in Nepal through unravelling the
   water-energy-agriculture nexus}},
Journal = {{INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF WATER RESOURCES DEVELOPMENT}},
Abstract = {{This article investigates water security in Nepal from the perspective
   of the water-energy-agriculture (food) nexus, focusing on pathways to
   water security that originate in actions and policies related to other
   sectors. It identifies promoting development of Nepal's hydropower
   potential to provide energy for pumping as way to improve water security
   in agriculture. Renewable groundwater reserves of 1.4 billion cubic
   meters (BCM), from an estimated available balance of 6.9 BCM, could be
   pumped to irrigate 613,000 ha of rainfed agricultural land in the Terai
   plains, with a potential direct economic gain of USD 1.1 billion
   annually and associated benefits including promotion of energy-based
   industry, food security and local employment. Governance also plays an
   important role in addressing water security. We conclude that a
   nexus-based approach is required for effective water management and
   governance.}},
