Pages = {{77-98}},
Abstract = {{Growing concerns over climate change and the potential for large damages
   due to nonlinear processes underscore the need for a meaningful
   sustainability assessment of an economy. Economists have developed
   rigorous approaches to conceptualizing sustainability based on the
   paradigm of weak sustainability, which relies on extensive substitution
   among reproducible capital, renewable resources, and exhaustible natural
   resources. In contrast, strong sustainability emphasizes physical limits
   to this substitution and the importance of maintaining the resilience of
   normally functioning biophysical processes. Recent progress in resource
   and environmental economics has demonstrated the feasibility of
   incorporating strong sustainability features, including tipping points,
   uncertainties, and resilience, to assess efficiency and optimal
   policies. Given that weak sustainability and intertemporal efficiency
   share a welfare theoretic foundation, we ask: To what extent can these
   approaches be applied to evaluate sustainability? We highlight recent
   work on assessing sustainability in imperfect economies and dynamic
   models of intertemporal welfare that embed strong sustainability
   features.}},
